[[File:Hair-rig.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Hair rig]]
The '''hair rig''' is a piece of [[fishing tackle]] which allows a [[Fishing bait|bait]] to be presented without sitting directly on the [[Fishing hook|hook]]. It is mainly associated with [[boilies]], but also works effectively with many other baits. The hair rig became popular in the 1970s. It has been experimented with by English anglers, and has revolutionised [[carp]] fishing.<ref>{{citebook|title=Fishing Tips for Freshwater: Over 500 Ways to Improve Your Fishing Skills|author=Stackpole Books|year= 2003|isbn=0-8117-2654-1}}</ref>

At the beginning, natural wire (from a ponytail) was used to link the bait to the hook. This is why it was called the 'hair rig'. This material was very discreet but it was a little fragile. The bait also didn't act in a sufficiently natural manner. In tests, the [[carp]] only took the free offerings and left the hook bait. It was also a problem because anglers sometimes lost their baits while they were casting.  These problems have been solved with the appearance of [[Braided fishing line|braided thread]], a new material that allows threads to be as discreet as natural ones but more resistant.

